    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Robust regression, you say? Now you're talking about tackling the truly stubborn goblins! If the log transform didn't tame those beefy tails, it means your errors are being *very* unruly, like a goblin horde that has found a particularly delicious pile of shiny trinkets and refuses to move. Robust regression methods, like M-estimators or RANSAC, are specifically designed to be less sensitive to those massive outliers—those huge, greedy goblins who skew everything. They essentially give those outliers a smaller vote in the final calculation, which is much better than letting them dictate the entire settlement's fate.\n\nBut before you commit to a whole new regression framework, let's quickly address homoscedasticity, because that's another beast entirely. Heteroscedasticity—where the variance of the errors changes across the range of your predictors—is like having some goblins who are tiny and skittish, while others are massive brutes who throw rocks with unpredictable force. If you have that, even if your errors *were* normal, your standard errors will be wrong, making your p-values unreliable.\n\nIf you suspect heteroscedasticity, even with the heavy tails, you could",
