      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you suspect heteroscedasticity, even with the heavy tails, you could **use Weighted Least Squares (WLS)**. WLS is like giving the smaller, more predictable goblins a bigger voice in the decision-making process, effectively down-weighting the influence of the observations where the error variance is known (or estimated) to be much larger. You'd need to model the variance structure first, which can be a bit of a scavenger hunt, but it keeps you firmly in the frequentist, linear-ish camp.\n\nNow, about MCMC and Bayesian methods... *Hmph*. Bayesian modeling is like inviting a whole council of very cautious, highly educated goblins into your camp. They don't just accept the data as it is; they build a whole probabilistic world around it. For severe non-normality and heavy tails, Bayesian methods *can* be incredibly helpful because you can specify much more flexible prior distributions for your error terms—you could explicitly tell the model, \"Hey, I expect these errors to look like a Student's t-distribution, not a perfect Gaussian bell curve.\" This allows the model to handle the \"beefy tails\" without forcing them into a normal shape.",
